metadata.name: Bonsai Bonanza #308
metadata.description:
In previous works, I was attracted by the idea of ‚Äã‚Äãthe domestication of plants.
According to Wikipedia, the purposes of bonsai are primarily contemplation for the viewer, and the pleasant exercise of effort and ingenuity for the grower. By contrast with other plant cultivation practices, bonsai is not intended for production of food or for medicine. Instead, bonsai practice focuses on long-term cultivation and shaping of one or more small trees growing in a container.
I pressume that the main intention is aesthetic. The beauty. Because we love beautiful things.
It is very interesting how we modify certain creatures for our sake of satisfaction.

May this collection brings you good fortune.

metadata.name: Alleles #279
metadata.description:
An allele, short for 'allelomorph', is an alternative version of a specific gene.

This collection (which is in no way scientifically accurate), was born out of an exercise in simplicity. Outputs are made up of arrangements of squares in various compositions, yet within that we are free to imagine what they could mean. For some, the resulting shapes might represent DNA strands or atoms. Others might see cells or the building blocks of the hereditary instructions that shape us as individuals. 

A generative genetic report accompanies each output to spark the imagination and attempt to attach further meaning to each composition. Some gene sequences carry mutations, however not all mutations are visually apparent. Please refer to the fxhash features to view the reports accordingly.

Texture is used subtly, so for maximum enjoyment it is recommended that you save and view your outputs at full size in order to best enjoy the details.

Press 'S' to save a 2400 x 3396 px PNG file.

attributes.name: Genetic Profile
attributes.value: Evaluation of the information extracted from the provided genetic information suggests subject may have a disposition tending towards infrequent periods of jealousy and egocentricity, yet also has the potential to display a high degree of creativity and kindness. Maximum potential hereditary height (excluding nutritional and environmental factors) is estimated at 123-132cm. Projected natural lifespan estimated at 89-93 years. Presence of mutation may require supervised observation to determine the presence of any superhuman abilities. It is advised that special attention be paid to markers 218 through 438, as these may indicate the presence of pyrokinesis and or accelerated cellular regeneration.

metadata.name: Emotional Shell #304
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 72 ¬∑ 54 ¬∑ 40 ¬∑ 30 ¬∑ 24 ¬∑ 20 every 8 minutes.
Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted, and then drop one price tier.

---------

The feeling of being human ‚Äì with all of its intricate hopes, struggles, and fleeting emotions ‚Äì seems so unique that we assume artificial intelligence could never replicate our experience. And while we devise systems for solving unfathomably complex problems, generating algorithmic creativity, and unlocking regenerative biological possibilities, we simultaneously cling to the power and originality of emotional feeling ‚Äì believing it to be the irreplaceable source of what makes us human.

If the body is our shell for emotion and soul, can an artificial humanoid be another vessel for these thoughts and feelings ‚Äì for human essence itself? If our ‚Äòsoul‚Äô is the last stand between us and the machines, what happens when the soul becomes transferable? That we may see answers to these questions looks more real every year, and is perhaps a little frightening. 

Emotional Shell uses introspective portraits of future selves to question what it means to be human, when the people around us are no longer human.

---------

Warning: This piece is GPU intensive, it may not render on lower end devices.

Press 1-3 to select from low, medium, and high quality settings
Press 'S' to save the image at the current scale
Press 'H' to save the image at 2400px resolution

Created with Three.js
For third party license information, please see bundle.js.LICENSE.txt

---------

metadata.name: La Veranada #95
metadata.description:
My mother lives in the countryside with her husband and her work is the breeding and grazing of goats, cows and horses. They live a cyclical life marked by two big stages during their livestock year: "La Veranada" and "La Invernada".
The "invernada" is the place where they live during what we could call the long winter, that is, from April to November. "La Invernada" is below, in the plains, in the pampas, in accessible places, where it is easy to supply the animals with fodder.
"La Veranada" is the place where they go during the long summer, from November to April, it is above, in the mountain ranges, on the heights, where the summer pastures abound, where they go for months to take care, alone, of the goats, cows and calves.
The transfer of the animals to the summer pasture is called "Arreo", my mother's husband guides the animals on his horse. The "Arreo" lasts about 5 days.
In both places they live in what they call "el puesto". "El puesto" is their home.
In "La veranada", "El puesto" is simple. A common living room, with a wood stove, a table, some chairs and shelves to store flour, *"mate" and salt. A small bedroom replenishes the strength worn out by the daily work. Water for drinking, cooking and washing is drawn from a nearby stream.
Work is abundant. As a common element, both in winter and summer, my mother's husband rides a horse daily and, accompanied by his dogs, goes to "watch" the cattle.
As a final point I wanted to thank you for taking your time and reading the story behind this project that I really enjoyed doing it, and on my tw profile you can read this story with real photos.

*Mate: is an Argentinean infusion, which is present all day long in the life of people who live in the countryside. It give you energy.

Press "S" in live mode to save image 2600 x 3000.
Please note that the algorithm can take some time to run.
Created by Fernando. NFT License 2.0.

metadata.name: Hello, World! (Fantasy) #52
metadata.description:
Based on the classic "Hello, world!" test, this project is a test of the FX Hash system. It implements a few technologies and things not yet tested by me on this platform. The work generated follows the "Hello, world!" format, varying the greeting and subject. The subject in this particular case is chosen from a limited set of emojis called "Fantasy" (specifically the "person-fantasy" subgroup of the "People-Body" emoji group).

The emojis used in this come from open source providers.

An "optional" feature (trait) is being tested which may affect rarity scores. No special rarity is given to any feature, however.

metadata.name: Southern Gothic #20
metadata.description:
‚ÄúSouthern Gothic‚Äù is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

‚ÄúSouthern Gothic‚Äù borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery O‚ÄôConnor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Limina #291
metadata.description:
Limina is a study of the fine line between order and chaos.

Each piece of the collection is made up of just one or two lines. These lines are defined by thousands of points that are chosen, one by one, by a simple algorithm moving across the canvas. What arises from that simple concept is a surprising variety of intricate patterns, accidental symmetries and traces of order in chaotic structures. 

Limina is a meditation on the concept of emergence, a concept that lies at the heart of generative art. The algorithm that defines the core of the series is only capable of making one simple choice: left, right, up or down? As it moves across the canvas, it leaves a trace of points that are connected by a curve. The order in which these points are chosen and the tightness of the curve connecting them is what creates the visual diversity of Limina. As these values fluctuate, symmetries emerge and break down again, forms, patterns and ornaments are created and combined to form both complex structures and simple abstractions. 

Limina shows the potential of minimalist generative concepts to generate visually dense and unexpected results. 

Press 's' to save your image.
